SIMPLE: hilarity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hilarity
<hw>Hi*lar"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>hilaritas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>hilarit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See
<er>Hilarious</er>.]</ety> <def>Boisterous mirth; merriment;
jollity.</def> <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Hilarity</xex> differs from <xex>joy</xex>: the
latter, excited by good news or prosperity, is an affection of the mind;
the former, produced by social pleasure, drinking, etc., which rouse the
animal spirits, is more demonstrative.</note></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Glee; cheerfulness; mirth; merriment; gayety;
joyousness; exhilaration; joviality; jollity.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hilary term</ent>⟦br⟧
